<LP>
   NEW YORK -- L. Gordon Crovitz, a senior member of The Wall
Street Journal's editorial board and columnist on legal
issues, was named editor of the Far Eastern Economic Review
effective May 1.
   Mr. Crovitz, 33 years old, joined the Journal in 1980 and
in 1983 became the first editorial page editor of The Wall
Street Journal Europe, based in Brussels. His legal column
has won five consecutive awards from the New York Bar
Association.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Review, published in Hong Kong with more than 72,000
subscribers and newsstand buyers, is a weekly magazine
providing reporting and analysis of Asian business, economic
and political affairs. Dow Jones &amp; Co., which also publishes
The Wall Street Journal, acquired full ownership of the
Review in 1987.
   Mr. Crovitz will have overall responsibility for the
editorial direction and coverage of the Review. He succeeds
Philip Bowring, 49, editor of the Review since 1988, who has
been offered a position as associate editor, Dow Jones Asia,
and as a regular columnist.
</TEXT>
